   176	<!-- ANCHOR:questions -->
   177	## 7. NON-FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
   178	
   179	### Reversibility
   180	- **NFR-R01**: Every step P0→P4 names an explicit rollback; the P4 global default-on keeps `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=0` as the documented, load-bearing kill-switch.
   181	- **NFR-R02**: Because compiled routing is byte-identical to legacy for matched hubs, any step's rollback is behavior-neutral by construction, not merely by test.
   182	
   183	### Determinism
   184	- **NFR-D01**: The fallback is deterministic: identical (hub config, manifest, flag) inputs always yield the same served-authority; drift is a pure function of a hash mismatch, not timing.
   185	
   186	### Authority
   187	- **NFR-A01**: Serving authority is conferred only by a valid, fresh manifest under an enabled flag for an eligible hub; nothing else grants it, and the eligibility predicate has exactly one source of truth (P3).
   188	
   189	---
   190	
   191	## 8. EDGE CASES
   192	
   193	### Fallback correctness
   194	- Hub with no manifest (a freshly created skill, pre-`013`): resolves to the legacy sentinel; routing unchanged — backward-compat by construction.
   195	- Hub with a stale manifest (config edited, not re-minted): live hash ≠ minted digest ⇒ legacy sentinel; P1 CI fails re-mint-required.
   196	
   197	### Observability boundaries
   198	- Drifted hub vs broken resolver: both currently read identically; P0 observability must separate "degraded/expected (drift)" from "broken (error)".
   199	- All-legacy fleet under flag-on: a valid state (e.g. every hub mid-edit), must read as degraded, not failed.
   200	
   201	### Kill-switch
   202	- `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=0` after P4 default-on: must fully restore legacy serving fleet-wide, documented as the kill-switch, not an incidental default.
   203	
